WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:05.000
So I think the, I asked Ted very last minute to

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:07.470
change the description of the talk and I didn't make it

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:07.570
.

00:00:07.590 --> 00:00:08.200
I don't blame him.

00:00:08.200 --> 00:00:10.460
He's a trans-dimensional being, so.

00:00:10.470 --> 00:00:14.130
The talk is actually about how, what the future of startups

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:16.600
looks like in the world of open data.

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:19.110
Not quite so much about, initially it was about like,

00:00:19.110 --> 00:00:22.440
you know, the experience I had working on a product with

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:24.410
lexicons that I didn't, you know, I

00:00:24.410 --> 00:00:25.770
didn't make a single original lexicon.

00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:26.960
And I was happy about that.

00:00:27.030 --> 00:00:27.580
That was a great thing.

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:30.460
But, you know, then it kind of expanded more,

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:33.980
especially when I started talking to the community a lot more.

00:00:33.990 --> 00:00:36.450
And then there's like sort of a bigger issue here about

00:00:36.450 --> 00:00:39.100
, you know, the computer kill mentality that's there in

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:41.520
conventional tech startups in the tech world.

00:00:41.530 --> 00:00:44.810
And what a huge opportunity we have to kind of change that

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:47.820
and disrupt that in the ad proto world or the world of

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:48.680
open data.

00:00:48.690 --> 00:00:50.420
So I want to talk about that a little bit.

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:53.180
So, yeah, let's get started.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:55.760
Let's dive into like a little bit of the old world

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:56.020
.

00:00:56.030 --> 00:00:57.680
Like, what the world looked like.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:00:59.100
Good old Microsoft, you know.

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:01.240
So Microsoft kind of kicked things off.

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:04.110
I mean, there's obviously like much, many more stories

00:01:04.130 --> 00:01:07.240
of how there's like this crazy competition outside of the tech

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:07.760
world.

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:09.550
But in the tech world, I think one of the biggest

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:11.470
stories that got us kicked off back in the 90s,

00:01:11.470 --> 00:01:15.160
this was 96, was Microsoft with their kind of like cut

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:17.140
throat, we must dominate mentality.

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:21.420
They kind of dominated the market for operating systems in the first

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:22.060
place.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:24.300
But on top of that, you know, when this new

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:27.320
thing called the Internet came out and they were like, we

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:28.860
've got to get in on that.

00:01:28.870 --> 00:01:32.660
So Netscape at the time was dominating the space with

00:01:32.890 --> 00:01:36.100
the Internet browser Netscape Navigator.

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:39.640
I think Mike McHugh is somewhere in this sphere.

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:42.080
So I'm glad he's not here because I hope I

00:01:42.110 --> 00:01:44.020
get all the details right.

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:47.600
But, yeah, Microsoft didn't quite like that.

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:49.960
And they were like, you know, we've got to

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:51.740
get ourselves in there fast.

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:54.540
So what they did was they noticed that everyone was using open

00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:55.280
standards.

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:57.380
And that's a way for them to kind of put themselves

00:01:57.380 --> 00:01:57.960
in there.

00:01:57.970 --> 00:01:59.620
Everyone's kind of like agreeing that, you know, we

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:01.250
've got to use these standards to kind of like build on

00:02:01.250 --> 00:02:01.780
the Internet.

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:03.690
So then they say, yeah, we're going to come

00:02:03.690 --> 00:02:05.400
in, we're going to embrace your standards.

00:02:05.410 --> 00:02:08.560
We're going to, you know, make sure that we

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:12.000
want to give the users the best, you know, even

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.260
when some of that is originated elsewhere, like from people contributing

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:16.100
to the ecosystem.

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:17.880
And then, you know, the next thing they do is

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:19.600
they extend it, being like, oh, we have to

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:21.620
, we're not going to hold back our users for waiting

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:24.420
for these like slow moving organizations and standards bodies.

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:26.760
You know, we're going to have to move fast and

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:28.620
do some of the things our own way.

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:31.910
And the well-being of those few people who aren't

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:35.000
our users is understandable, but also not a high priority,

00:02:35.070 --> 00:02:35.840
you know.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:39.480
And then eventually that goes to Extinguish, where they

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:43.660
did this with ActiveX and Internet Explorer extensions to kind of

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:47.290
like dominate the market share and kind of make sure that they

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:49.820
are the only ones who kind of stay in there.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:52.900
So the rationale for that is like, why should we expend

00:02:52.910 --> 00:02:55.090
effort towards keeping competitors viable?

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.000
Why shouldn't we actively help potential customers join us?

00:02:58.050 --> 00:02:59.340
You know, why do we have to care anymore?

00:02:59.350 --> 00:03:01.910
So suddenly the same, you know, standards that they were

00:03:01.910 --> 00:03:04.340
embracing, they have kind of weaponized that to kind of

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:05.910
keep all the competitors out.

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:09.000
And, you know, of course, they can also just

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.870
tell all the PC manufacturers they're working with, if you

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:14.320
work with Netscape, we're going to stop supplying

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:14.960
you.

00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:16.340
So, you know, that's another way to just like

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:17.220
kill your competitors.

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:19.690
You know, so it's kind of crazy how Nets

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:22.820
cape was literally 90% in 1995.

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:25.720
And in the span of like seven years, like, you

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.360
know, it flipped completely to 5%, you know.

00:03:28.370 --> 00:03:32.160
And Internet Explorer took over because of these sort of practices.

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:35.090
And, you know, AOL acquires Netscape

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:37.710
by the end of this, so they kind of get a

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:39.310
nice, cushy exit.

00:03:39.330 --> 00:03:43.600
Okay, a bunch of people have had a chance to kind

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:45.640
of dunk on the Zuck.

00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:46.840
It's my turn, okay.

00:03:46.890 --> 00:03:48.440
So this is the thing.

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:51.270
He spent years shouting domination at the end of Facebook.

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:52.100
Like, that's so weird.

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:53.270
Like, I mean, imagine doing that at the end of

00:03:53.350 --> 00:03:54.520
a meeting, being like, domination.

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:55.340
What?

00:03:55.350 --> 00:03:56.720
What a strange guy.

00:03:56.730 --> 00:04:00.300
And, you know, this is another thing that the guy

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:03.320
, the Zuck, is capable of, you know.

00:04:03.330 --> 00:04:06.170
Like, he was working with Harvard to do the Facebook,

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:08.550
but, you know, he's just giving out the data

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:09.700
to other people.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:11.570
That's the kind of person that kind of comes up with

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:13.280
this competition attitude, you know.

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:14.580
That's like, I mean, I'm dunking on

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:16.000
Zuck for sure, but like there's a sort of

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.480
domination attitude, which is an abstraction that I'm trying to

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:19.400
point towards here.

00:04:20.830 --> 00:04:23.260
And to ground it more in sort of like the same story

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.620
as Microsoft from earlier.

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:26.800
So we're all familiar with Snap, and we kind of

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:27.880
lived through this.

00:04:27.890 --> 00:04:31.180
I was actively using Snap as a teenager at that point.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:34.750
And, you know, what was going on behind the scenes

00:04:34.750 --> 00:04:39.690
at that point was in 2012, Facebook acquired Instagram for $

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:40.940
1 billion.

00:04:41.450 --> 00:04:44.020
And they, I think within a year, they wanted to

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:47.660
acquire Snapchat because Snapchat was like this hot new thing.

00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:48.710
All the kids were using it.

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:51.800
They wanted to, you know, grab those little kids in

00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:54.070
a, you know, probably weird way.

00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:56.930
But Snapchat declined the offer.

00:04:56.950 --> 00:04:59.110
And I think there was a subsequent offer from Google as well

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:00.320
, which they also declined.

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:03.480
And they continued to grow over those years.

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:06.350
Like for a solid three or four years after that, Snapchat

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.300
went up to 150 million users.

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:12.360
But then, don't be too proud to copy.

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:14.250
That was actually from a memo that was in Facebook.

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:18.580
You know, they said, we should just rip those off

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:18.920
.

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:19.600
We have Instagram.

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:21.490
Let's just put stories in there.

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:22.420
You know, they launched stories.

00:05:22.450 --> 00:05:27.770
In one year, when they launched Instagram, when Snapchat had

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:32.020
150 million users, within one year, Instagram had overtaken

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:32.850
that, you know.

00:05:32.870 --> 00:05:35.650
And there was, like, I mean, for the previous

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:38.390
story, there was at least an anti-compete for

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:39.520
that scenario.

00:05:39.530 --> 00:05:40.940
And antitrust, rather.

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:44.360
And Microsoft did actually face some repercussions.

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:47.840
Not that it really stopped them in the grand scheme.

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:48.830
But here, nothing happened.

00:05:48.850 --> 00:05:51.710
You know, Snapchat exists as a husk of itself,

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:54.220
doing whatever people there do now.

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:57.770
And, you know, this attitude of, like, copying

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:01.150
things has pervaded, you know, Facebook.

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:02.440
But not just Facebook, you know.

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:05.210
Like, within Facebook alone, you have stories that become Snapchat

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:05.310
.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:08.060
You have reels from TikTok and threads.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:10.560
Like, they built threads in, I think, in five

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.300
months, which is, you know, pretty insane.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:14.430
And there's a point there.

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:17.010
That these guys, at some point, the biggest guys,

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:18.760
they become brokers of scale.

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:20.560
The large companies become brokers of scale.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:23.130
And they're able to stay dominant because they have the means

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:25.510
and ability to deploy things at scale really fast.

00:06:25.530 --> 00:06:27.920
And they have the users.

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:28.740
They have the distribution.

00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:29.780
They have the network effects.

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:32.020
And if you're some kind of, like, upstart

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:36.180
with a genuinely innovative product and idea, you become big enough

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:39.520
to get to the point where they'll notice you.

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:41.040
And then they're kind of, you know, they're

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:42.420
going to decide your fate at that point.

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:47.140
And I want to look at this now from the founder perspective

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:48.400
, you know.

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:50.870
If you're building a company, like, you want to

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:52.500
create something of value.

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:53.820
And then you want to grow.

00:06:53.830 --> 00:06:56.080
And then, like, kind of the meta now, if

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:58.300
you're a startup, you know, or, like,

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.220
a founder, an entrepreneur, you want to, like,

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:01.680
sell to the broker of scale.

00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:03.570
Like, this is actually, this isn't a failure.

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:04.910
This is, like, the expected outcome.

00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:07.360
Like, founders now in, like, all these startup universities

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:09.080
, they're taught to do this stuff, you know.

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:11.810
Like, this is kind of, like, we've accepted

00:07:11.810 --> 00:07:14.540
that this is how the life cycle of a product, of

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:16.180
a new innovative thing should be.

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:18.420
And it's just, like, you know, it's

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:21.800
first you build something that people love, you know.

00:07:21.830 --> 00:07:23.520
There's a whole user side of this.

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:25.160
Users start relying on your product.

00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:27.030
They start, you know, integrating it into their lives.

00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:28.360
They start trusting it with their data.

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:30.540
They start using it to find their community and build their community

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:30.680
.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:34.240
There were some conversations I had with community members here and,

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:35.560
of course, about meetup.

00:07:35.560 --> 00:07:35.840
com.

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:38.550
Maybe you guys have had some bad experiences yourself, you know

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:39.780
, where you're paying a bunch of money.

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:41.960
And, you know, what's really happening there?

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:44.400
You know, there's, like, I think I was

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:48.740
talking to someone who said that meetup sent them a notice

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:50.260
being, like, oh, you're our, like,

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.900
I think you've brought, like, 10,000 people

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:55.480
or reached 10,000 people to the network.

00:07:55.490 --> 00:07:57.010
And also, by the way, can you pay us for

00:07:57.010 --> 00:07:57.740
the next year?

00:07:57.750 --> 00:07:59.240
It's like, you should be paying them, man.

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:02.000
But anyway, that's almost a separate point.

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:04.560
But the point is here is that you kind of grow something

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:05.800
until you're visible.

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:08.690
And then when you sell, as an entrepreneur, if you

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:10.960
sell, the product is a sacrifice.

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:13.530
Like, the users who have now spent all this time building

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:16.730
a relationship with what you've built, now it's,

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:22.000
they're kind of, you know, they become the sacrifice

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:22.400
.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:23.900
Like, all of that is sacrificed.

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:27.320
Yeah, and the other note here is, like, scale

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:28.750
doesn't matter.

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:31.300
Like, Instagram, with its 30 million users, was a

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:34.200
1 billion purchase, 400 million users for WhatsApp.

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:38.370
Oculus, that was more of, like, a hardware remote

00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:38.680
.

00:08:38.690 --> 00:08:41.020
And be real, this is kind of a newer example.

00:08:41.190 --> 00:08:42.940
I just found this out while researching this talk.

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:44.640
It had 40 million users.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:46.110
And, you know, like, even now, it's

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:48.040
like, it doesn't matter if you hit the scale.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:50.050
If you hit a scale that's kind of big enough,

00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:51.720
big tech just comes in and swoops in.

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:54.380
Because they just have to continue to dominate.

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:55.680
It's just a mandate of domination.

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:00.180
And, yeah, to go back to the earlier point,

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:02.070
it's just, you know, I'm going to use

00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:03.480
some Cory Doctorow stuff here.

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:06.260
The n-shittification starts happening, you know.

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:08.910
This is, like, the eventual decline and death of products

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:09.130
.

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:11.510
You know, people have, like, opinions about Doctorow

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.350
and the word n-shittification, but it is

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:14.260
a true concept.

00:09:14.270 --> 00:09:15.680
It's something that happens to us, you know.

00:09:15.690 --> 00:09:19.010
I don't know if you guys have watched the movie Pentagon

00:09:19.010 --> 00:09:19.500
Wars.

00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:20.660
It's fantastic.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:24.890
It's about, basically, the Pentagon, they have this

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:28.570
Bradley fighting vehicle, which is, like, this, a

00:09:28.570 --> 00:09:29.010
tank.

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:31.360
But, you know, people, people aren't exactly sure

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:31.980
what it is.

00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:33.760
Like, people get promoted to be in charge of it.

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:35.650
They slap on a new feature, then they get promoted to

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:36.660
work on something else.

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:39.680
And then this goes on for, like, a while.

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:42.490
And Kelsey Grammer, he's, you know, the

00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:43.560
guy in charge.

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:45.980
But then, at some point, an airline guy comes in

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:48.060
to vet the product, and he finds out that it doesn

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:49.480
't work, it doesn't do anything.

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:51.700
And people aren't even sure what it's supposed to do

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:53.540
, because it's supposed to be, like, submarine.

00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:54.520
It's supposed to be a land.

00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:55.500
It's supposed to be troop transport.

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:56.180
It has a gun.

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:59.400
And so the point here and the analogy here is that,

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:02.390
you know, eventually the big tech, like, when they

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:05.220
have their own products, like Google or Spotify, they start

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:06.200
slapping on these features.

00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:08.260
People get promoted, you know, to a higher position,

00:10:08.270 --> 00:10:09.680
and then they stop caring about it.

00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:10.880
They move on to other things.

00:10:10.910 --> 00:10:12.420
And then, ultimately, you just have, like, this

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:14.010
mess of, like, 50 different things going on.

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:16.190
The user is, like, I actually just wanted these three

00:10:16.190 --> 00:10:18.390
things that I always had before, you know.

00:10:19.750 --> 00:10:22.420
And if you're a big company, this is what happens

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:22.640
.

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:24.480
If you're a startup, you sell your company, and

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:26.250
then it becomes part of this machine where the same thing happens

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:26.540
.

